    "1. The distortion design worked as intended.\n",
    "Forecast paths were oversmoothed along the time axis and then recentered/rescaled back to the benchmark on a per-horizon basis. The preservation checks were essentially zero, showing that horizon-wise mean and standard deviation were restored almost exactly. This suggests that Type 3a mainly isolates temporal dependence distortion, rather than introducing location or spread contamination.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. VS is the dominant detector for Type 3a.\n",
    "Under the null case (K=0), the VS rejection rate stayed close to the nominal level. However, once smoothing was introduced, VS rejection rose almost immediately to full power. Even at K=1, the rejection rate was already about 0.99, and for larger K it was effectively 1.00. This indicates that the lag-restricted variogram score is extremely sensitive to this type of temporal dependence misspecification.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. ES is much less sensitive to this distortion.\n",
    "The ES rejection rate remained close to the nominal level across almost all values of K, with only a slight increase at the strongest smoothing level. This suggests that, for this particular error type, ES is not nearly as responsive as VS. The result supports the intended interpretation of VS as a dependence-sensitive complement to ES.\n",
    "Marginal tests remained largely unaffected.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. KS, AD, and 90% coverage rejection rates all stayed close to 5% across the severity grid. This is an important result because it shows that Type 3a did not materially damage marginal calibration. In other words, the distortion primarily affected the dependence structure, not the marginal distribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "5. Ljung–Box did not show a strong power pattern.\n",
    "The Ljung–Box rejection rates did not increase systematically with K and remained fairly similar to their null behavior. This suggests that, in this setup, PIT-based serial dependence diagnostics were much less informative than VS for detecting the imposed oversmoothing distortion.\n",
    "\n",
    "6. The prototype ACF check and the Monte Carlo results are consistent.\n",
    "The prototype analysis already showed that smoothing created clear lag dependence and that the anchored recenter/rescale step did not remove the core signal. The Monte Carlo results confirm the same conclusion at scale: the distortion is real, and VS captures it very effectively."
