    "1. Initial expectation\n",
    "The main expectation was that ES would act as the primary detector, because Type 3b modifies the joint dependence structure rather than the marginal distributions.\n",
    "VS was treated as a secondary diagnostic.\n",
    "KS, AD, Ljung–Box, and coverage were expected to remain comparatively weak.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Main result: thresholded diagnostics\n",
    "The rejection rates did not show a clear or monotone increase across the \n",
    "Δ𝜌 grid. In particular, ES did not display strong power under this distortion.\n",
    "VS also remained close to nominal.\n",
    "KS, AD, Ljung–Box, and coverage stayed broadly near their null levels.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Follow-up check: horizon-wise 2D ES\n",
    "To examine whether the lack of signal might be caused by high-dimensional dilution in the full-path ES, a supplementary lower-dimensional continuous-score check was conducted.\n",
    "\n",
    "For each horizon t, a bivariate ES was computed on the 2D ensemble\n",
    "using the same frozen pooled benchmark scaling as in Phase A / B.\n",
    "\n",
    "These horizon-wise 2D ES values were then averaged across horizons to produce a single scalar per replication.\n",
    "\n",
    "Continuous-score result\n",
    "The horizon-wise 2D ES remained essentially flat across the  Δρ grid.\n",
    "Both the means and medians showed only very small variation relative to their Monte Carlo dispersion.\n",
    "There was no clear pattern in which the score increased with ∣Δρ∣, and no obvious evidence that Δρ=0 behaved as a distinct minimum.\n",
    "\n",
    "The supplementary 2D ES check suggests that the weak Type 3b result is not simply due to the high dimensionality of the original full-path ES.\n",
    "Instead, under the current setup, perturbing the contemporaneous cross-variable correlation alone does not generate a strong detection signal for ES. This is consistent with the theoretical property of ES as a distance-based scoring rule: under equal marginal distributions, a change in cross-variable correlation has limited impact on the expected Euclidean distance between forecast and realized vectors\n",
    "\n",
    "This means that Type 3b, in its current form, does not provide a strong supporting case for ES as a detector of cross-variable dependence misspecification.\n",
    "Practical conclusion\n",
    "\n",
    "Type 3b should be treated as an optional / exploratory branch, rather than a central result.\n",
    "\n",
    "The main dependence result of Phase C should therefore remain Type 3a, where VS showed a very strong and interpretable response."
   ]
  },
